WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.946 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:00.946 --> 00:00:01.446 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:01.446 --> 00:00:04.820 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:04.820 --> 00:00:11.400 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:17.040 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So last time,
we more or less finished

00:00:17.040 --> 00:00:24.990 align:middle line:84%
discussing quantization of
the free scalar field theory.

00:00:24.990 --> 00:00:30.210 align:middle line:84%
And then we showed that the
excitations of that theory

00:00:30.210 --> 00:00:35.880 align:middle line:84%
essentially give rise to
relativistic particles.

00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:39.510 align:middle line:84%
And so we also discussed
various other things--

00:00:39.510 --> 00:00:43.200 align:middle line:84%
so structure of
the Hilbert space,

00:00:43.200 --> 00:00:45.360 align:middle line:90%
conserved quantities, et cetera.

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:48.760 align:middle line:90%


00:00:48.760 --> 00:00:53.050 align:middle line:84%
So at the end, we
talked about how

00:00:53.050 --> 00:01:04.890 align:middle line:84%
to understand the conserved
charge at the quantum level.

00:01:04.890 --> 00:01:19.940 align:middle line:90%


00:01:19.940 --> 00:01:26.390 align:middle line:84%
So classically-- so we have a,
say, symmetric transformation--

00:01:26.390 --> 00:01:32.180 align:middle line:84%
means that if you take phi
a to some phi a prime--

00:01:32.180 --> 00:01:37.230 align:middle line:84%
phi a prime, normally, we write
it in the infinitesimal way--

00:01:37.230 --> 00:01:41.030 align:middle line:84%
introduce some parameter
a-- some parameter epsilon.

00:01:41.030 --> 00:01:43.710 align:middle line:84%
And I can also have
multiple symmetries.

00:01:43.710 --> 00:01:47.200 align:middle line:84%
So for each transformation--
say I have epsilon.

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:53.420 align:middle line:84%
So alpha labels different
transformations, and then--

00:01:53.420 --> 00:01:57.080 align:middle line:84%
so this is the transformation,
which can depend on phi a.

00:01:57.080 --> 00:02:01.890 align:middle line:84%
Also depends on its
derivatives, et cetera.

00:02:01.890 --> 00:02:04.370 align:middle line:84%
And then if you have such
a symmetric transformation

00:02:04.370 --> 00:02:09.030 align:middle line:84%
we discussed before, then that
generates a conserved current,

00:02:09.030 --> 00:02:10.889 align:middle line:90%
and that is labeled by alpha.

00:02:10.889 --> 00:02:13.710 align:middle line:84%
Alpha just denotes
different conserved current.

00:02:13.710 --> 00:02:16.710 align:middle line:84%
And then yeah, so
it is conserved.

00:02:16.710 --> 00:02:21.480 align:middle line:90%


00:02:21.480 --> 00:02:25.060 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
classical statement.

00:02:25.060 --> 00:02:27.370 align:middle line:84%
Oh, yeah, also Noether's
theorem tells us

00:02:27.370 --> 00:02:29.450 align:middle line:84%
how to write down such
a current explicitly.

00:02:29.450 --> 00:02:32.280 align:middle line:90%


00:02:32.280 --> 00:02:35.220 align:middle line:90%
So we can just write it as--

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:37.050 align:middle line:84%
the current can be
written explicitly.

00:02:37.050 --> 00:02:48.800 align:middle line:90%


00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:55.580 align:middle line:84%
So k mu is the transformation
of the Lagrangian density.

00:02:55.580 --> 00:02:57.800 align:middle line:84%
Suppose under this
transformation the Lagrangian

00:02:57.800 --> 00:03:04.290 align:middle line:84%
density transform as, say,
alpha partial mu, k mu alpha.

00:03:04.290 --> 00:03:06.830 align:middle line:90%


00:03:06.830 --> 00:03:08.300 align:middle line:90%
So alpha, it doesn't matter.

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:11.030 align:middle line:84%
Alpha just label different
symmetries-- the index.

00:03:11.030 --> 00:03:15.970 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't matter
whether it's up or down.

00:03:15.970 --> 00:03:21.908 align:middle line:84%
And then the zeroth
component of the charge--

00:03:21.908 --> 00:03:24.200 align:middle line:84%
zeroth component of the
current when you integrate over

00:03:24.200 --> 00:03:29.220 align:middle line:84%
all space then give rise
to a conserved charge.

00:03:29.220 --> 00:03:40.620 align:middle line:84%
So this is conserved
charge times the--

00:03:40.620 --> 00:03:42.720 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:43.920 align:middle line:90%
So now, let's discuss--

00:03:43.920 --> 00:03:46.570 align:middle line:90%


00:03:46.570 --> 00:03:49.340 align:middle line:84%
so when you go to
quantum level--

00:03:49.340 --> 00:03:52.390 align:middle line:84%
so when you quantize the
theory, and this just becomes

00:03:52.390 --> 00:03:55.060 align:middle line:84%
quantum operator,
and the whole current

00:03:55.060 --> 00:03:57.040 align:middle line:90%
becomes a quantum operator.

00:03:57.040 --> 00:04:02.080 align:middle line:84%
And then Q is also
a quantum operator.

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:03.010 align:middle line:90%
So the quantum level--

00:04:03.010 --> 00:04:10.080 align:middle line:90%


00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:11.970 align:middle line:90%
and now Q alpha--

00:04:11.970 --> 00:04:14.850 align:middle line:84%
because it's conserved,
so this becomes

00:04:14.850 --> 00:04:16.410 align:middle line:90%
time-independent operator.

00:04:16.410 --> 00:04:22.930 align:middle line:90%


00:04:22.930 --> 00:04:27.310 align:middle line:84%
We see explicitly in the case
of the, say, Hamiltonian dens--

00:04:27.310 --> 00:04:30.020 align:middle line:90%
Hamiltonian and the momentum.

00:04:30.020 --> 00:04:34.420 align:middle line:84%
So we showed explicitly they
actually don't depend on time.

00:04:34.420 --> 00:04:36.130 align:middle line:84%
But at the quantum
mechanical level,

00:04:36.130 --> 00:04:38.980 align:middle line:84%
actually, this Q can play
a more important role.

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:43.100 align:middle line:90%


00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:46.950 align:middle line:84%
In fact, it can be viewed as
a generator of symmetries.

00:04:46.950 --> 00:04:47.630 align:middle line:90%
So we can show--

00:04:47.630 --> 00:04:51.080 align:middle line:90%


00:04:51.080 --> 00:04:54.660 align:middle line:84%
we will show the
following statement--

00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:58.860 align:middle line:84%
that if you consider
so epsilon--

00:04:58.860 --> 00:05:00.510 align:middle line:90%
so consider such a quantity--

00:05:00.510 --> 00:05:04.050 align:middle line:90%


00:05:04.050 --> 00:05:07.870 align:middle line:84%
can you see the commutator
of Q with phi a.

00:05:07.870 --> 00:05:12.110 align:middle line:90%


00:05:12.110 --> 00:05:14.000 align:middle line:84%
So now, let's
continue over to here.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.030 align:middle line:90%


00:05:17.030 --> 00:05:19.050 align:middle line:90%
Maybe just let me write it here.

00:05:19.050 --> 00:05:26.040 align:middle line:84%
And that generates minus
epsilon alpha f alpha a.

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:31.590 align:middle line:84%
So the commutator of this Q
alpha epsilon alpha with phi a

00:05:31.590 --> 00:05:35.790 align:middle line:84%
essentially generates this
transformation, essentially,

00:05:35.790 --> 00:05:38.250 align:middle line:84%
generate this infinitesimal
transformation.

00:05:38.250 --> 00:05:41.490 align:middle line:90%


00:05:41.490 --> 00:05:45.240 align:middle line:84%
So that's why we call the
Q alpha also generator

00:05:45.240 --> 00:05:46.410 align:middle line:90%
of symmetries.

00:05:46.410 --> 00:05:54.660 align:middle line:90%


00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:57.960 align:middle line:84%
So this is the statement
I'm going to show very soon.

00:05:57.960 --> 00:06:01.390 align:middle line:84%
So before I do that, do
you have any questions?

00:06:01.390 --> 00:06:02.080 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:06:02.080 --> 00:06:04.360 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: In the conserved
current equation,

00:06:04.360 --> 00:06:07.840 align:middle line:84%
how can f have an alpha
in the upper index

00:06:07.840 --> 00:06:10.803 align:middle line:84%
when J has an alpha in the
lower index, its not meaningful?

00:06:10.803 --> 00:06:11.470 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:06:11.470 --> 00:06:14.200 align:middle line:84%
Just alpha-- don't worry about
the location of alpha index.

00:06:14.200 --> 00:06:19.750 align:middle line:84%
Alpha just label a different
current and just went-- yeah,

00:06:19.750 --> 00:06:22.060 align:middle line:84%
here, we don't worry
about its notation.

00:06:22.060 --> 00:06:25.660 align:middle line:84%
I just put it up and down
just for convenience.

00:06:25.660 --> 00:06:28.910 align:middle line:90%


00:06:28.910 --> 00:06:31.310 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:06:31.310 --> 00:06:32.315 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:06:32.315 --> 00:06:33.940 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can you
[INAUDIBLE] positions

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:36.020 align:middle line:90%
is that a sum over alpha?

00:06:36.020 --> 00:06:37.550 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Sorry?

00:06:37.550 --> 00:06:40.340 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: In the
proposed, var L is

00:06:40.340 --> 00:06:43.730 align:middle line:84%
epsilon alpha partial to
mu alpha, is that a sum

00:06:43.730 --> 00:06:44.720 align:middle line:90%
over all alpha?

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:47.540 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that's
sum over all alphas.

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:50.990 align:middle line:90%
So any repeated indices is sum.

00:06:50.990 --> 00:06:52.880 align:middle line:90%
So if you only have one--

00:06:52.880 --> 00:06:55.710 align:middle line:84%
so for example, if you have
one epsilon-- of course,

00:06:55.710 --> 00:06:58.740 align:middle line:84%
there is no sum, but if you
have two different charges,

00:06:58.740 --> 00:06:59.990 align:middle line:90%
and then this is sum.

00:06:59.990 --> 00:07:02.600 align:middle line:90%


00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:03.590 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:07:03.590 --> 00:07:08.760 align:middle line:90%


00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:12.500 align:middle line:84%
So we are going to
show this statement.

00:07:12.500 --> 00:07:14.050 align:middle line:84%
And so this statement
is very easy

00:07:14.050 --> 00:07:19.210 align:middle line:90%
to show in the general case.

00:07:19.210 --> 00:07:22.480 align:middle line:84%
So let me call
this equation star.

00:07:22.480 --> 00:07:26.410 align:middle line:84%
So let's first
consider the case--

00:07:26.410 --> 00:07:29.665 align:middle line:84%
first, let's consider
the sub case that the--

00:07:29.665 --> 00:07:33.360 align:middle line:90%


00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:44.100 align:middle line:84%
let's first suppose f a alpha--
just this transformation

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:56.580 align:middle line:84%
of phi a does not contain
the time derivative of phi a.

00:07:56.580 --> 00:08:05.070 align:middle line:84%
And also the zeroth component
of the k is equal to 0.

00:08:05.070 --> 00:08:10.560 align:middle line:90%
Let's consider a first spec--

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:11.685 align:middle line:90%
a more limited case.

00:08:11.685 --> 00:08:16.830 align:middle line:90%


00:08:16.830 --> 00:08:18.890 align:middle line:84%
So this more limited
case actually

00:08:18.890 --> 00:08:22.510 align:middle line:90%
covers many, many examples.

00:08:22.510 --> 00:08:26.280 align:middle line:84%
It actually covers a
majority of examples.

00:08:26.280 --> 00:08:29.580 align:middle line:84%
For example, if you look at
the translation symmetry,

00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:32.510 align:middle line:84%
which gives rise to
the stress tensor--

00:08:32.510 --> 00:08:36.690 align:middle line:84%
so this will-- so this
applies to the case I mu--

00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:38.650 align:middle line:90%
T mu i.

00:08:38.650 --> 00:08:41.380 align:middle line:84%
So this corresponding
to the spatial--

00:08:41.380 --> 00:08:44.890 align:middle line:84%
so this is the conserved current
corresponding to the spatial.

00:08:44.890 --> 00:08:50.950 align:middle line:84%
So this is the current
for spatial translations.

00:08:50.950 --> 00:08:56.820 align:middle line:90%


00:08:56.820 --> 00:08:59.710 align:middle line:84%
When we do spatial
translations, then of course,

00:08:59.710 --> 00:09:04.590 align:middle line:84%
this f given by the
spatial derivatives,

00:09:04.590 --> 00:09:07.890 align:middle line:84%
and then it does not
involve time derivative.

00:09:07.890 --> 00:09:12.120 align:middle line:84%
And in that case, the k
also does not involve in--

00:09:12.120 --> 00:09:13.350 align:middle line:90%
k 0 component's 0.

00:09:13.350 --> 00:09:15.590 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, just I try
to remind myself

00:09:15.590 --> 00:09:17.820 align:middle line:90%
of what you worked in your pset.

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:24.330 align:middle line:84%
And so for this example,
i is the counterpart--

00:09:24.330 --> 00:09:25.770 align:middle line:90%
is the alpha here.

00:09:25.770 --> 00:09:30.390 align:middle line:84%
So for each direction, you have
a translation, and so this--

00:09:30.390 --> 00:09:34.170 align:middle line:84%
so the alpha-- of course,
i is the alpha here

00:09:34.170 --> 00:09:35.940 align:middle line:90%
and the mu is the J mu here.

00:09:35.940 --> 00:09:39.670 align:middle line:90%


00:09:39.670 --> 00:09:44.610 align:middle line:84%
And also this applies
to the case which--

00:09:44.610 --> 00:09:49.200 align:middle line:90%
for all internal symmetries.

00:09:49.200 --> 00:09:58.000 align:middle line:90%


00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.360 align:middle line:84%
By internal symmetries, we
mean the transformations don't

00:10:01.360 --> 00:10:04.660 align:middle line:90%
involve space-time coordinates.

00:10:04.660 --> 00:10:07.390 align:middle line:84%
For example, you
did in your pset

00:10:07.390 --> 00:10:11.395 align:middle line:84%
the complex scalar field which
you can just rotate by phase.

00:10:11.395 --> 00:10:13.270 align:middle line:84%
And that's called the
internal transformation

00:10:13.270 --> 00:10:15.220 align:middle line:84%
because that
transformation does not

00:10:15.220 --> 00:10:18.910 align:middle line:90%
involve spacetime coordinates.

00:10:18.910 --> 00:10:21.970 align:middle line:84%
In contrast, when we
find the stress tensor,

00:10:21.970 --> 00:10:24.970 align:middle line:84%
we will do a
spacetime translation,

00:10:24.970 --> 00:10:28.480 align:middle line:90%
and that does involve spacetime.

00:10:28.480 --> 00:10:31.960 align:middle line:84%
So this corresponding to the
spacetime transformations--

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:32.950 align:middle line:90%
spacetime symmetries.

00:10:32.950 --> 00:10:36.070 align:middle line:84%
And this is-- the phase is
the internal symmetries.

00:10:36.070 --> 00:10:41.050 align:middle line:84%
So for all internal symmetries,
you don't-- the transformation

00:10:41.050 --> 00:10:43.020 align:middle line:84%
will not contain
the time derivative.

00:10:43.020 --> 00:10:46.090 align:middle line:90%


00:10:46.090 --> 00:10:51.970 align:middle line:84%
So in this case, then it's
easy because in this case,

00:10:51.970 --> 00:10:57.130 align:middle line:84%
then we just have the one-- then
the zeroth component of J mu.

00:10:57.130 --> 00:11:00.200 align:middle line:90%
J just given by--

00:11:00.200 --> 00:11:05.540 align:middle line:84%
the first term by definition
is just the canonical momentum

00:11:05.540 --> 00:11:11.090 align:middle line:90%
conjugate to the a.

00:11:11.090 --> 00:11:16.550 align:middle line:84%
So the first factor, partial L
partial partial mu phi a-- when

00:11:16.550 --> 00:11:18.440 align:middle line:90%
you set mu equal to 0--

00:11:18.440 --> 00:11:20.270 align:middle line:84%
so that's just the
derivative with respect

00:11:20.270 --> 00:11:23.180 align:middle line:84%
to the time derivative of phi
a, and that, by definition,

00:11:23.180 --> 00:11:30.020 align:middle line:84%
is just the canonical momentum
density conjugate to phi a.

00:11:30.020 --> 00:11:37.252 align:middle line:90%
And then you have f alpha a--

00:11:37.252 --> 00:11:38.130 align:middle line:90%
f a alpha.

00:11:38.130 --> 00:11:42.940 align:middle line:90%


00:11:42.940 --> 00:11:43.440 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:51.450 align:middle line:90%


00:11:51.450 --> 00:11:57.650 align:middle line:84%
So let me just make one
comment on this expression.

00:11:57.650 --> 00:12:01.690 align:middle line:84%
So this expression, of
course, classically, you

00:12:01.690 --> 00:12:03.800 align:middle line:90%
can write whatever way you want.

00:12:03.800 --> 00:12:05.350 align:middle line:84%
But quantum
mechanically, there's

00:12:05.350 --> 00:12:08.740 align:middle line:84%
a very important subtlety
because this typically

00:12:08.740 --> 00:12:13.360 align:middle line:84%
will involve phi, and
then this is momentum,

00:12:13.360 --> 00:12:15.430 align:middle line:84%
and they don't
necessarily commute.

00:12:15.430 --> 00:12:18.550 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
field theory version

00:12:18.550 --> 00:12:23.590 align:middle line:84%
of so-called operator ordering
ambiguity, which is already

00:12:23.590 --> 00:12:24.670 align:middle line:90%
in quantum mechanics.

00:12:24.670 --> 00:12:28.388 align:middle line:84%
In quantum mechanics, when
you go from classical--

00:12:28.388 --> 00:12:30.430 align:middle line:84%
even it's already in the
non-relativistic quantum

00:12:30.430 --> 00:12:31.000 align:middle line:90%
mechanics.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:32.710 align:middle line:84%
When you go to
classical mechanics

00:12:32.710 --> 00:12:34.720 align:middle line:84%
to quantum mechanics,
and then there's

00:12:34.720 --> 00:12:37.630 align:middle line:84%
an issue how you order
operators when you

00:12:37.630 --> 00:12:41.200 align:middle line:90%
have x and p at the same time.

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:51.670 align:middle line:84%
So here, you also have potential
operator ordering ambiguity.

00:12:51.670 --> 00:12:53.080 align:middle line:90%
You have to pay attention.

00:12:53.080 --> 00:12:58.910 align:middle line:90%


00:12:58.910 --> 00:13:01.640 align:middle line:84%
Often, such kind of
ambiguities can be resolved

00:13:01.640 --> 00:13:03.810 align:middle line:90%
by physical considerations.

00:13:03.810 --> 00:13:09.350 align:middle line:84%
So we will see some
examples in a little bit.

00:13:09.350 --> 00:13:12.353 align:middle line:90%


00:13:12.353 --> 00:13:13.770 align:middle line:84%
So now, let's just
imagine there's

00:13:13.770 --> 00:13:16.560 align:middle line:84%
some ordering we
have chosen, and now

00:13:16.560 --> 00:13:18.060 align:middle line:90%
let's look at this commutator.

00:13:18.060 --> 00:13:25.940 align:middle line:90%


00:13:25.940 --> 00:13:28.740 align:middle line:84%
So we can just write
down the definition.

00:13:28.740 --> 00:13:34.240 align:middle line:84%
So this is just integrating
over all spatial direction

00:13:34.240 --> 00:13:40.690 align:middle line:84%
epsilon alpha, and then we
have pi a f a alpha phi a.

00:13:40.690 --> 00:13:43.300 align:middle line:90%


00:13:43.300 --> 00:13:45.320 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, let me just--

00:13:45.320 --> 00:13:49.850 align:middle line:84%
sorry-- here, let me call
phi b, because the phi a--

00:13:49.850 --> 00:13:51.180 align:middle line:90%
now, they are differ--

00:13:51.180 --> 00:13:54.400 align:middle line:90%
so these two indices are summed.

00:13:54.400 --> 00:13:58.910 align:middle line:84%
So let me call them b, and
then you have phi a here.

00:13:58.910 --> 00:14:04.640 align:middle line:84%
So now, you can use commutation
relation between the momentum

00:14:04.640 --> 00:14:08.750 align:middle line:90%
density and the phi phi.

00:14:08.750 --> 00:14:12.770 align:middle line:84%
So we discussed in
general that the--

00:14:12.770 --> 00:14:15.320 align:middle line:90%
so we discussed the scalar case.

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:20.060 align:middle line:84%
But in general, you have this
commutation relation of--

00:14:20.060 --> 00:14:24.740 align:middle line:90%
which is delta 3--

00:14:24.740 --> 00:14:30.200 align:middle line:84%
say if this is the x,
and this is x prime,

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:34.690 align:middle line:84%
and then this is x minus
x prime, and delta ab.

00:14:34.690 --> 00:14:40.420 align:middle line:84%
So each one is only have a
