00:33:20.770 --> 00:33:25.362 align:middle line:84%
And so another example
is the phase rotation

00:33:25.362 --> 00:33:26.820 align:middle line:84%
if you have a
complex scalar field.

00:33:26.820 --> 00:33:48.962 align:middle line:90%


00:33:48.962 --> 00:33:51.295 align:middle line:84%
So there, we show there's a
Noether charge corresponding

00:33:51.295 --> 00:33:54.970 align:middle line:84%
to the phase rotation, there's
a Noether current corresponding

00:33:54.970 --> 00:33:57.520 align:middle line:84%
to rotating the
phase to the field.

00:33:57.520 --> 00:33:58.720 align:middle line:90%
That's a symmetry.

00:33:58.720 --> 00:34:05.302 align:middle line:84%
And so that will generate
the charge Q corresponding

00:34:05.302 --> 00:34:06.010 align:middle line:90%
to the first two.

00:34:06.010 --> 00:34:08.699 align:middle line:90%
And then if you have alpha Q--

00:34:08.699 --> 00:34:13.110 align:middle line:84%
and then when you act
on phi, and then you

00:34:13.110 --> 00:34:15.389 align:middle line:84%
can just check explicitly
that will generate the phase

00:34:15.389 --> 00:34:16.469 align:middle line:90%
rotation in phi.

00:34:16.469 --> 00:34:22.580 align:middle line:90%


00:34:22.580 --> 00:34:24.710 align:middle line:84%
And we're generating
phase rotation phi.

00:34:24.710 --> 00:34:39.960 align:middle line:90%


00:34:39.960 --> 00:34:40.994 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

00:34:40.994 --> 00:34:46.504 align:middle line:90%


00:34:46.504 --> 00:34:47.004 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:34:47.004 --> 00:34:56.820 align:middle line:90%


00:34:56.820 --> 00:35:06.025 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so let's conclude our
