OK, great.

00:35:28.940 --> 00:35:33.395 align:middle line:84%
So now, let's very
quickly talk about--

00:35:33.395 --> 00:35:51.500 align:middle line:90%


00:35:51.500 --> 00:35:54.365 align:middle line:84%
so let's very quickly talk
about complex scalar field.

00:35:54.365 --> 00:36:11.200 align:middle line:90%


00:36:11.200 --> 00:36:15.160 align:middle line:84%
And you can see the
complex scalar field,

00:36:15.160 --> 00:36:16.090 align:middle line:90%
we get something new.

00:36:16.090 --> 00:36:19.207 align:middle line:84%
We get the concept
of antiparticle.

00:36:19.207 --> 00:36:21.540 align:middle line:84%
So now, let's consider the
following Lagrangian density.

00:36:21.540 --> 00:36:25.340 align:middle line:90%


00:36:25.340 --> 00:36:28.680 align:middle line:84%
Again, we only consider
the quadratic--

00:36:28.680 --> 00:36:34.736 align:middle line:84%
the simplest-- only quadratic
Lagrangian, but now the phi

00:36:34.736 --> 00:36:35.236 align:middle line:90%
is complex.

00:36:35.236 --> 00:36:44.336 align:middle line:90%


00:36:44.336 --> 00:36:45.470 align:middle line:90%
Phi is complex.

00:36:45.470 --> 00:36:50.840 align:middle line:90%


00:36:50.840 --> 00:36:55.205 align:middle line:84%
So complex is also
the same as 2 real.

00:36:55.205 --> 00:36:59.350 align:middle line:90%


00:36:59.350 --> 00:37:04.880 align:middle line:84%
So you can decompose
phi into its real part

00:37:04.880 --> 00:37:06.930 align:middle line:90%
and imaginary part.

00:37:06.930 --> 00:37:10.550 align:middle line:84%
And if you plug them
in here, and then

00:37:10.550 --> 00:37:13.220 align:middle line:84%
you find you just get
two separate pieces,

00:37:13.220 --> 00:37:16.880 align:middle line:84%
and one is the real scalar
field for the real part

00:37:16.880 --> 00:37:21.410 align:middle line:84%
and the one is the free scalar
field for the imaginary part,

00:37:21.410 --> 00:37:24.612 align:middle line:84%
because each one-- yeah, if you
write phi equal to a plus ib,

00:37:24.612 --> 00:37:27.050 align:middle line:84%
and here, it just become
a squared plus b squared,

00:37:27.050 --> 00:37:30.740 align:middle line:84%
here, it's also
a plus b squared.

00:37:30.740 --> 00:37:33.090 align:middle line:90%
But there's a reason we write--

00:37:33.090 --> 00:37:35.420 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so essentially,
we just get two copies

00:37:35.420 --> 00:37:37.880 align:middle line:90%
of our previous theory.

00:37:37.880 --> 00:37:40.310 align:middle line:84%
We just get two copies
of previous theory.

00:37:40.310 --> 00:37:41.813 align:middle line:84%
So you say, oh,
then it's trivial.

00:37:41.813 --> 00:37:43.730 align:middle line:84%
Why should we just
consider this-- we just get

00:37:43.730 --> 00:37:46.010 align:middle line:90%
two copies of previous theory?

00:37:46.010 --> 00:37:50.535 align:middle line:84%
But this advantage-- but
there's some concept--

00:37:50.535 --> 00:37:55.145 align:middle line:84%
there's something conceptually
new when we write in this form.

00:37:55.145 --> 00:37:56.770 align:middle line:84%
there's advantage to
write in this form

00:37:56.770 --> 00:38:01.180 align:middle line:84%
rather than write as two
separate identical scalar

00:38:01.180 --> 00:38:02.680 align:middle line:90%
field theory.

00:38:02.680 --> 00:38:04.360 align:middle line:90%
It's precisely in this form--

00:38:04.360 --> 00:38:08.270 align:middle line:90%


00:38:08.270 --> 00:38:12.500 align:middle line:90%
this phase symmetry is manifest.

00:38:12.500 --> 00:38:15.530 align:middle line:84%
If I just write it as
two separate real scalar

00:38:15.530 --> 00:38:19.940 align:middle line:84%
field, then this phase
symmetry is not manifest.

00:38:19.940 --> 00:38:22.280 align:middle line:84%
And so here, in
this form, there's

00:38:22.280 --> 00:38:24.140 align:middle line:90%
a phase symmetry manifest.

00:38:24.140 --> 00:38:28.910 align:middle line:84%
So phi goes to
exponential i alpha phi.

00:38:28.910 --> 00:38:33.050 align:middle line:84%
And so you see this-- you
immediately see that symmetry.

00:38:33.050 --> 00:38:35.000 align:middle line:84%
So this-- when you
write it in terms

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:38.000 align:middle line:84%
of real and imaginary
part, this corresponding

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:40.970 align:middle line:84%
to a rotation between the
real and imaginary part.

00:38:40.970 --> 00:38:47.660 align:middle line:90%
And yeah-- good?

00:38:47.660 --> 00:38:50.270 align:middle line:84%
And the equation of
motion is the same

00:38:50.270 --> 00:38:51.590 align:middle line:90%
because it's just the--

00:38:51.590 --> 00:38:54.770 align:middle line:90%


00:38:54.770 --> 00:38:57.150 align:middle line:84%
because you can easily find
the equation of motion.

00:38:57.150 --> 00:38:57.740 align:middle line:90%
It's the same.

00:38:57.740 --> 00:39:00.350 align:middle line:90%


00:39:00.350 --> 00:39:06.760 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, because just two
copies of your previous theory.

00:39:06.760 --> 00:39:09.340 align:middle line:84%
Of course, the equation of
motion should be the same.

00:39:09.340 --> 00:39:12.480 align:middle line:90%
And the Lagrangian density--

00:39:12.480 --> 00:39:17.110 align:middle line:84%
the momentum
density for phi then

00:39:17.110 --> 00:39:24.930 align:middle line:84%
becomes partial 0 phi star,
and the partial phi star

00:39:24.930 --> 00:39:27.040 align:middle line:90%
becomes partial 0 phi.

00:39:27.040 --> 00:39:30.250 align:middle line:84%
So we treat-- we can
treat phi and the phi star

00:39:30.250 --> 00:39:32.680 align:middle line:90%
as two independent fields.

00:39:32.680 --> 00:39:35.530 align:middle line:84%
And then the
canonical momentum--

00:39:35.530 --> 00:39:38.470 align:middle line:84%
say if you take derivative
with partial 0 phi,

00:39:38.470 --> 00:39:42.040 align:middle line:84%
then you get the partial
0 phi star and vice versa.

00:39:42.040 --> 00:39:45.850 align:middle line:84%
So the complex conjugate
momentum like that.

00:39:45.850 --> 00:39:50.580 align:middle line:90%


00:39:50.580 --> 00:39:52.170 align:middle line:84%
So we can now
write down-- again,

00:39:52.170 --> 00:39:56.870 align:middle line:84%
we can just write down the
most general solutions.

00:39:56.870 --> 00:39:59.160 align:middle line:84%
So the basis of
solutions is the same.

00:39:59.160 --> 00:40:02.100 align:middle line:90%


00:40:02.100 --> 00:40:10.950 align:middle line:90%
Same set of solutions as before.

00:40:10.950 --> 00:40:27.640 align:middle line:84%
We just have u k x equal to
minus i omega k t plus i k x,

00:40:27.640 --> 00:40:33.380 align:middle line:90%
and then you have u k x star.

00:40:33.380 --> 00:40:37.257 align:middle line:84%
Because it's the same equation,
so the basis of the equation,

00:40:37.257 --> 00:40:38.840 align:middle line:84%
of course, is also
the same as before.

00:40:38.840 --> 00:40:39.760 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:40:39.760 --> 00:40:43.900 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So if the field
is an operator, doesn't it--

00:40:43.900 --> 00:40:48.010 align:middle line:84%
