00:40:48.010 --> 00:40:50.110 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: No, the fields--

00:40:50.110 --> 00:40:51.550 align:middle line:90%
it depends.

00:40:51.550 --> 00:40:58.060 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, indeed if it's
something directly observable,

00:40:58.060 --> 00:41:02.530 align:middle line:84%
it has to be Hermitian, but
that can have two observables.

00:41:02.530 --> 00:41:05.860 align:middle line:84%
For example, I can combine
them into a real variable.

00:41:05.860 --> 00:41:07.510 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, just not
necessarily the phi

00:41:07.510 --> 00:41:09.340 align:middle line:84%
itself have to be
directly observable.

00:41:09.340 --> 00:41:10.105 align:middle line:90%
It's just a field.

00:41:10.105 --> 00:41:13.340 align:middle line:90%


00:41:13.340 --> 00:41:15.170 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, the field itself
don't have to always

00:41:15.170 --> 00:41:16.700 align:middle line:90%
be observable by itself.

00:41:16.700 --> 00:41:19.243 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So then the conjugate
momentum also is not--

00:41:19.243 --> 00:41:19.910 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:41:19.910 --> 00:41:21.890 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The momentum is
not our three momentum?

00:41:21.890 --> 00:41:23.640 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, this
