We have a k star,
say, classically.

00:42:33.300 --> 00:42:35.070 align:middle line:84%
Let me just first
write classically.

00:42:35.070 --> 00:42:38.220 align:middle line:90%
So previously, we have this.

00:42:38.220 --> 00:42:40.500 align:middle line:84%
Previously, why we
have a k star here

00:42:40.500 --> 00:42:41.955 align:middle line:84%
when we have a
real scalar field?

00:42:41.955 --> 00:42:47.800 align:middle line:90%


00:42:47.800 --> 00:42:50.060 align:middle line:84%
It's because the
field has to be real,

00:42:50.060 --> 00:42:53.290 align:middle line:84%
and then we have always add
to its complex conjugate.

00:42:53.290 --> 00:42:57.670 align:middle line:84%
But now, the difference is
that now phi is a complex,

00:42:57.670 --> 00:42:59.120 align:middle line:90%
and the phi is complex.

00:42:59.120 --> 00:43:01.990 align:middle line:84%
And then we no longer
have the real condition.

00:43:01.990 --> 00:43:06.460 align:middle line:84%
That means here, I can choose
another arbitrary constant

00:43:06.460 --> 00:43:07.810 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:43:07.810 --> 00:43:09.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
arbitrary constant.

00:43:09.590 --> 00:43:12.160 align:middle line:84%
So by convention, let
me just put a star here.

00:43:12.160 --> 00:43:12.980 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't matter.

00:43:12.980 --> 00:43:15.460 align:middle line:90%
It's just the name you call it.

00:43:15.460 --> 00:43:19.090 align:middle line:84%
So now, the most
general solution--

00:43:19.090 --> 00:43:20.460 align:middle line:90%
now, you have two sets.

00:43:20.460 --> 00:43:22.650 align:middle line:84%
You have a, which
is complex number.

00:43:22.650 --> 00:43:25.530 align:middle line:84%
Then you have another
complex number, which is b.

00:43:25.530 --> 00:43:29.000 align:middle line:84%
Now, you have two sets
of complex numbers.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:33.230 align:middle line:84%
And it makes sense because when
you have a complex variable,

00:43:33.230 --> 00:43:34.790 align:middle line:84%
you double the
degrees of freedom,

00:43:34.790 --> 00:43:36.740 align:middle line:84%
and your integration
constant also doubled.

00:43:36.740 --> 00:43:39.750 align:middle line:90%


00:43:39.750 --> 00:43:45.070 align:middle line:90%
So b k independent of a.

00:43:45.070 --> 00:43:49.910 align:middle line:90%


00:43:49.910 --> 00:43:54.140 align:middle line:84%
So now, you have two
sets of variables.

00:43:54.140 --> 00:43:56.840 align:middle line:84%
So you can get the phi
star just by taking

00:43:56.840 --> 00:43:59.630 align:middle line:90%
the complex conjugate of it--

00:43:59.630 --> 00:44:02.510 align:middle line:84%
just by taking the
complex conjugate of it.

00:44:02.510 --> 00:44:19.480 align:middle line:84%
And then the full set of
integration constant just--

00:44:19.480 --> 00:44:21.520 align:middle line:90%
you have a k--

00:44:21.520 --> 00:44:29.340 align:middle line:84%
you have a k star, you have
b k, and you have b k star.

00:44:29.340 --> 00:44:30.645 align:middle line:90%
So this is the classical story.

00:44:30.645 --> 00:44:34.010 align:middle line:90%


00:44:34.010 --> 00:44:40.550 align:middle line:84%
So now, for quantum, we just
do exactly as we did before.

00:44:40.550 --> 00:44:44.570 align:middle line:84%
You just promoted all those
into operating equations.

00:44:44.570 --> 00:44:49.160 align:middle line:84%
So the-- so you just
call this dagger.

00:44:49.160 --> 00:44:52.970 align:middle line:84%
Just call this dag-- just view
every one of them as operators.

00:44:52.970 --> 00:44:56.140 align:middle line:84%
And now, this just becomes
constant operators.

00:44:56.140 --> 00:45:00.500 align:middle line:90%


00:45:00.500 --> 00:45:03.920 align:middle line:84%
And now, here, you also
just call them to be dagger.

00:45:03.920 --> 00:45:15.620 align:middle line:90%


00:45:15.620 --> 00:45:17.475 align:middle line:90%
And the-- yeah.

00:45:17.475 --> 00:45:24.990 align:middle line:90%


00:45:24.990 --> 00:45:28.050 align:middle line:90%
So now, equal time commutation--

00:45:28.050 --> 00:45:35.210 align:middle line:84%
still, we have to impose
the equal time commutation

00:45:35.210 --> 00:45:35.710 align:middle line:90%
relation.

00:45:35.710 --> 00:46:06.100 align:middle line:90%


00:46:06.100 --> 00:46:07.960 align:middle line:84%
So now, we have to
impose the equal time

00:46:07.960 --> 00:46:13.010 align:middle line:90%
commutation relations again.

00:46:13.010 --> 00:46:15.350 align:middle line:90%
So this all should be simple.

00:46:15.350 --> 00:46:18.770 align:middle line:84%
So we should have
phi, phi dagger.

00:46:18.770 --> 00:46:21.285 align:middle line:84%
They can be-- they're considered
as independent operators,

00:46:21.285 --> 00:46:22.910 align:middle line:84%
so they should commute
with each other.

00:46:22.910 --> 00:46:26.150 align:middle line:84%
They're all field variables,
and the phi actually

00:46:26.150 --> 00:46:28.260 align:middle line:90%
commutes with itself.

00:46:28.260 --> 00:46:31.100 align:middle line:84%
So this is all evaluated at
different spatial-- yeah,

00:46:31.100 --> 00:46:34.730 align:middle line:84%
just to save time, I will
not write this expression,

00:46:34.730 --> 00:46:38.330 align:middle line:84%
but all this should be
evaluated at the same time

00:46:38.330 --> 00:46:56.830 align:middle line:84%
by different spatial locations
such as all these equal to 0.

00:46:56.830 --> 00:46:59.890 align:middle line:84%
Except the only thing
which is non-zero

00:46:59.890 --> 00:47:03.445 align:middle line:84%
is the phi with its
own canonical momentum.

00:47:03.445 --> 00:47:07.440 align:middle line:90%


00:47:07.440 --> 00:47:08.880 align:middle line:90%
So everything else will be 0.

00:47:08.880 --> 00:47:14.835 align:middle line:84%
The only thing non-zero is phi,
which is canonical momentum.

00:47:14.835 --> 00:47:18.510 align:middle line:90%


00:47:18.510 --> 00:47:25.230 align:middle line:84%
Again, it should be given by
i delta 3 x minus x prime.

00:47:25.230 --> 00:47:27.840 align:middle line:84%
And then the similar
thing for the phi dagger.

00:47:27.840 --> 00:47:34.420 align:middle line:90%


00:47:34.420 --> 00:47:36.910 align:middle line:90%
So again, I save effort.

00:47:36.910 --> 00:47:40.305 align:middle line:90%


00:47:40.305 --> 00:47:41.680 align:middle line:84%
So that's what
you should impose.

00:47:41.680 --> 00:47:44.480 align:middle line:90%


00:47:44.480 --> 00:47:47.420 align:middle line:84%
So now, if you plug
those things in,

00:47:47.420 --> 00:47:51.080 align:middle line:84%
then you can find the
commutation relation

00:47:51.080 --> 00:47:52.625 align:middle line:90%
between a and a dagger.

00:47:52.625 --> 00:47:57.140 align:middle line:90%


00:47:57.140 --> 00:48:09.770 align:middle line:84%
Again, you find-- and
similarly, with b,

00:48:09.770 --> 00:48:12.500 align:middle line:90%
you just get two sides of--

00:48:12.500 --> 00:48:15.920 align:middle line:84%
two infinite family of
harmonic oscillators.

00:48:15.920 --> 00:48:20.750 align:middle line:84%
Previously, we have one family,
and now you get two families,

00:48:20.750 --> 00:48:22.985 align:middle line:84%
and all other
commutators vanish.

00:48:22.985 --> 00:48:28.270 align:middle line:90%


00:48:28.270 --> 00:48:29.530 align:middle line:90%
So this part is boring.

00:48:29.530 --> 00:48:34.930 align:middle line:84%
You can almost guess everything
without doing any calculations.

00:48:34.930 --> 00:48:40.053 align:middle line:90%


00:48:40.053 --> 00:48:41.470 align:middle line:84%
You essentially
guessed everything

00:48:41.470 --> 00:48:43.168 align:middle line:90%
without doing any calculation.

00:48:43.168 --> 00:48:46.920 align:middle line:90%


00:48:46.920 --> 00:48:48.950 align:middle line:84%
So now, again, you can
write the Hamiltonian

00:48:48.950 --> 00:48:51.080 align:middle line:90%
in terms of a k and b k.

00:48:51.080 --> 00:48:55.880 align:middle line:84%
Just will be as you
would guess them to be.

00:48:55.880 --> 00:48:57.830 align:middle line:84%
Just the harmonic
oscillator corresponding

00:48:57.830 --> 00:49:00.110 align:middle line:84%
to a k, harmonic oscillator
corresponding to b k.

00:49:00.110 --> 00:49:03.800 align:middle line:90%


00:49:03.800 --> 00:49:08.170 align:middle line:84%
And then the ground
state-- again,

00:49:08.170 --> 00:49:12.250 align:middle line:84%
it's the state annihilated
by both of them.

00:49:12.250 --> 00:49:15.700 align:middle line:90%


00:49:15.700 --> 00:49:16.975 align:middle line:90%
So this is the vacuum state.

00:49:16.975 --> 00:49:20.420 align:middle line:90%


00:49:20.420 --> 00:49:25.780 align:middle line:84%
And now, you can
act a k dagger on 0

00:49:25.780 --> 00:49:30.090 align:middle line:90%
and b k dagger on 0, et cetera.

00:49:30.090 --> 00:49:33.290 align:middle line:90%


00:49:33.290 --> 00:49:35.540 align:middle line:84%
So now, we have two
kinds of particles.

00:49:35.540 --> 00:50:11.850 align:middle line:90%


00:50:11.850 --> 00:50:34.560 align:middle line:84%
So now, we have two kinds of
particles generated by a k

00:50:34.560 --> 00:50:40.230 align:middle line:90%
dagger and b k dagger now.

00:50:40.230 --> 00:50:47.700 align:middle line:84%
So now you have two kinds
of particles respectively,

00:50:47.700 --> 00:50:53.310 align:middle line:84%
and both of them have
the on-shell condition.

00:50:53.310 --> 00:51:00.030 align:middle line:84%
Both particles
have the same mass.

00:51:00.030 --> 00:51:06.450 align:middle line:84%
They satisfy the P squared
equal to m squared --

00:51:06.450 --> 00:51:08.130 align:middle line:90%
minus m squared.

00:51:08.130 --> 00:51:10.380 align:middle line:84%
So because they all come
from the same equation.

00:51:10.380 --> 00:51:17.870 align:middle line:90%


00:51:17.870 --> 00:51:21.470 align:middle line:84%
So now, the question is,
how do we tell them apart?

00:51:21.470 --> 00:51:24.830 align:middle line:84%
Now, we have two
types of particles.

00:51:24.830 --> 00:51:30.420 align:middle line:84%
They have the same
mass, and we--

00:51:30.420 --> 00:51:34.727 align:middle line:84%
yeah, just by definition,
they don't have any--

00:51:34.727 --> 00:51:35.560 align:middle line:90%
they have same mass.

00:51:35.560 --> 00:51:37.690 align:middle line:84%
They also have the same
spin because they're

00:51:37.690 --> 00:51:39.400 align:middle line:90%
all spin 0 scalar particles.

00:51:39.400 --> 00:51:42.750 align:middle line:90%
There's no directions.

00:51:42.750 --> 00:51:47.070 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, the question is,
how do we tell them apart?

00:51:47.070 --> 00:52:04.950 align:middle line:90%


00:52:04.950 --> 00:52:07.425 align:middle line:84%
So here is this U(1)
symmetry becomes useful.

00:52:07.425 --> 00:52:10.190 align:middle line:90%


00:52:10.190 --> 00:52:13.060 align:middle line:84%
Here is this U(1)
symmetry becomes useful.

00:52:13.060 --> 00:52:21.490 align:middle line:84%
So this U(1) so this phase
rotation is a symmetry.

00:52:21.490 --> 00:52:25.610 align:middle line:84%
And mathematically, this is
called the U(1) transformation.

00:52:25.610 --> 00:52:29.680 align:middle line:84%
So this is normally
called U(1) symmetry.

00:52:29.680 --> 00:52:35.710 align:middle line:84%
U(1) is just a mathematical
term for phase rotation--

00:52:35.710 --> 00:52:37.690 align:middle line:84%
mathematically,
it's a U(1) group.

00:52:37.690 --> 00:52:39.260 align:middle line:90%
It's a mathematical term for--

00:52:39.260 --> 00:52:45.450 align:middle line:90%


00:52:45.450 --> 00:52:50.670 align:middle line:84%
so the way we take them apart is
by looking at their conserved--

00:52:50.670 --> 00:52:52.320 align:middle line:90%
look at their quantum numbers.

00:52:52.320 --> 00:52:55.260 align:middle line:84%
If we look at two particles,
then how do we tell them apart?

00:52:55.260 --> 00:52:57.640 align:middle line:84%
We look at their
quantum numbers.

00:52:57.640 --> 00:52:59.500 align:middle line:84%
And they're quantum
numbers, so far,

00:52:59.500 --> 00:53:03.000 align:middle line:84%
they look almost the same
because their mass is the same.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:05.000 align:middle line:84%
And by definition, they
are scalar particles,

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:06.545 align:middle line:90%
and so they have 0--

00:53:06.545 --> 00:53:09.960 align:middle line:84%
they're spin 0--
they don't have spin.

00:53:09.960 --> 00:53:12.552 align:middle line:84%
And so the only other
conserved number--

00:53:12.552 --> 00:53:14.510 align:middle line:84%
yeah, if you want to talk
about quantum number,

00:53:14.510 --> 00:53:17.210 align:middle line:84%
their quantum number
has got to be conserved,

00:53:17.210 --> 00:53:19.160 align:middle line:84%
because otherwise, if
it changes with time,

00:53:19.160 --> 00:53:22.400 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't matter-- it doesn't
make sense to use that number

00:53:22.400 --> 00:53:23.930 align:middle line:90%
to label a particle.

00:53:23.930 --> 00:53:26.960 align:middle line:84%
But we get one more conserved
number corresponding

00:53:26.960 --> 00:53:30.350 align:middle line:90%
to this symmetry.

00:53:30.350 --> 00:53:32.730 align:middle line:90%
So this U(1) symmetry--

00:53:32.730 --> 00:53:37.920 align:middle line:84%
so Noether's theorem-- yeah,
from the Noether's theorem,

00:53:37.920 --> 00:53:39.480 align:middle line:90%
so this is U(1) symmetry--

00:53:39.480 --> 00:53:43.470 align:middle line:90%


00:53:43.470 --> 00:53:46.240 align:middle line:84%
then tell us there's
a conserved charge.

00:53:46.240 --> 00:53:48.740 align:middle line:90%
So if you work it out--

00:53:48.740 --> 00:53:50.230 align:middle line:84%
you work out the
loss theorem, then

00:53:50.230 --> 00:53:53.170 align:middle line:84%
you find the corresponding
conserved charge, which you

00:53:53.170 --> 00:53:55.180 align:middle line:90%
should have already worked out.

00:53:55.180 --> 00:53:59.320 align:middle line:84%
So let me just write
it classically.

00:53:59.320 --> 00:54:02.745 align:middle line:84%
So I just write
them as phi star.

00:54:02.745 --> 00:54:04.620 align:middle line:84%
So classically, they
have the following form.

00:54:04.620 --> 00:54:11.580 align:middle line:90%


00:54:11.580 --> 00:54:16.160 align:middle line:84%
So at the quantum level,
this becomes operators.

00:54:16.160 --> 00:54:19.890 align:middle line:90%
But here, there's an operator--

00:54:19.890 --> 00:54:22.580 align:middle line:84%
but now, here,
there's an operator

00:54:22.580 --> 00:54:26.270 align:middle line:84%
of-- when we go to
the quantum level,

00:54:26.270 --> 00:54:30.110 align:middle line:84%
now there's an operator
ordering ambiguity now.

00:54:30.110 --> 00:54:37.460 align:middle line:84%
You see, here, the phi don't
commute with its own conjugate

00:54:37.460 --> 00:54:39.830 align:middle line:90%
momentum.

00:54:39.830 --> 00:54:42.020 align:middle line:84%
And so here, we
have phi multiply

00:54:42.020 --> 00:54:43.770 align:middle line:90%
its conjugate momentum.

00:54:43.770 --> 00:54:46.400 align:middle line:84%
And if we change
the order, and then

00:54:46.400 --> 00:54:49.070 align:middle line:90%
we will result a delta function.

00:54:49.070 --> 00:54:53.050 align:middle line:90%


00:54:53.050 --> 00:54:56.882 align:middle line:84%
And that will give
rise to infinite nu--

00:54:56.882 --> 00:54:57.382 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:54:57.382 --> 00:55:00.300 align:middle line:90%


00:55:00.300 --> 00:55:07.560 align:middle line:84%
So at the quantum level,
different ordering--

00:55:07.560 --> 00:55:15.740 align:middle line:90%


00:55:15.740 --> 00:55:26.155 align:middle line:84%
differ by some
infinite constant.

00:55:26.155 --> 00:55:30.940 align:middle line:90%


00:55:30.940 --> 00:55:32.955 align:middle line:84%
So you can take
phi, and you can--

00:55:32.955 --> 00:55:34.330 align:middle line:84%
yeah, if you change
the ordering,

00:55:34.330 --> 00:55:36.040 align:middle line:90%
then you get a delta function.

00:55:36.040 --> 00:55:39.940 align:middle line:84%
But delta function,
again, is evaluated

00:55:39.940 --> 00:55:42.610 align:middle line:84%
because these two is
evaluated at the same x,

00:55:42.610 --> 00:55:45.528 align:middle line:84%
and then you get the delta
function evaluated at the 0.

00:55:45.528 --> 00:55:47.320 align:middle line:84%
So essentially, you
get infinite constants.

00:55:47.320 --> 00:55:49.910 align:middle line:90%


00:55:49.910 --> 00:56:15.840 align:middle line:84%
But we can fix this ambiguity
by requiring your vacuum

00:56:15.840 --> 00:56:19.050 align:middle line:84%
state-- your lowest energy
state should have charge

00:56:19.050 --> 00:56:22.970 align:middle line:84%
0, because by definition, when
you're at the lowest energy,

00:56:22.970 --> 00:56:24.170 align:middle line:90%
there's nothing there.

00:56:24.170 --> 00:56:27.440 align:middle line:90%
It's a vacuum.

00:56:27.440 --> 00:56:32.780 align:middle line:84%
By requiring the lowest
energy state, have charge 0.

00:56:32.780 --> 00:56:38.060 align:middle line:84%
So that uniquely fixes
whatever infinite--

00:56:38.060 --> 00:56:40.210 align:middle line:90%
the ordering.

00:56:40.210 --> 00:56:45.700 align:middle line:84%
So by requiring this
equal to 0, and then you

00:56:45.700 --> 00:56:47.630 align:middle line:90%
can show that the Q--

00:56:47.630 --> 00:56:49.780 align:middle line:90%
so now, you can essentially--

00:56:49.780 --> 00:56:51.265 align:middle line:90%
the Q has the following form.

00:56:51.265 --> 00:56:58.310 align:middle line:90%


00:56:58.310 --> 00:56:59.720 align:middle line:90%
So you can already--

00:56:59.720 --> 00:57:07.040 align:middle line:84%
you may be able to guess the
answer of a k dagger a k, then

00:57:07.040 --> 00:57:11.450 align:middle line:90%
minus b k dagger b k.

00:57:11.450 --> 00:57:13.640 align:middle line:90%
That's what you get.

00:57:13.640 --> 00:57:17.660 align:middle line:84%
So you plug those
expressions in.

00:57:17.660 --> 00:57:20.450 align:middle line:84%
You plug those expressions
at this time derivative.

00:57:20.450 --> 00:57:22.610 align:middle line:90%
Time derivative gives you pi.

00:57:22.610 --> 00:57:24.920 align:middle line:84%
You just plug those
expressions in,

00:57:24.920 --> 00:57:27.290 align:middle line:84%
and again, you find--
because this is conserved,

00:57:27.290 --> 00:57:30.300 align:middle line:84%
you find all these time
dependents cancel, et cetera.

00:57:30.300 --> 00:57:34.420 align:middle line:84%
And then you get these
two expressions up

00:57:34.420 --> 00:57:37.650 align:middle line:90%
to some constant.

00:57:37.650 --> 00:57:43.260 align:middle line:84%
And then this condition requires
that that constant must be 0.

00:57:43.260 --> 00:57:46.500 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, when you
write in this form.

00:57:46.500 --> 00:57:48.930 align:middle line:84%
You see this annihlates
the Q because the a is

00:57:48.930 --> 00:57:50.730 align:middle line:84%
on the right-hand
side of a dagger.

00:57:50.730 --> 00:57:54.570 align:middle line:84%
So this automatically
annihilates the vacuum.

00:57:54.570 --> 00:58:01.950 align:middle line:90%


00:58:01.950 --> 00:58:05.330 align:middle line:84%
So essentially, this is
just occupation number

00:58:05.330 --> 00:58:08.210 align:middle line:84%
for a and this occupation
number for b k.

00:58:08.210 --> 00:58:20.050 align:middle line:90%


00:58:20.050 --> 00:58:22.050 align:middle line:90%
So we essentially get Q--

00:58:22.050 --> 00:58:28.930 align:middle line:90%


00:58:28.930 --> 00:58:31.330 align:middle line:84%
essentially, the
occupation number

00:58:31.330 --> 00:58:36.460 align:middle line:84%
for a k and the
occupation number for b k.

00:58:36.460 --> 00:58:40.890 align:middle line:84%
So occupation number,
I just write as N. Yes?

