01:10:21.462 --> 01:10:22.670 align:middle line:90%
This is-- I don't understand.

01:10:22.670 --> 01:10:23.990 align:middle line:84%
I don't know how
to think about it.

01:10:23.990 --> 01:10:26.365 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that's why
we call it internal symmetry.

01:10:26.365 --> 01:10:28.860 align:middle line:90%


01:10:28.860 --> 01:10:33.750 align:middle line:84%
So for things that we don't
have good intuition about,

01:10:33.750 --> 01:10:35.610 align:middle line:84%
you just invent the
new name for it--

01:10:35.610 --> 01:10:36.690 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

01:10:36.690 --> 01:10:39.150 align:middle line:84%
--and once you get
used to this new name,

01:10:39.150 --> 01:10:42.060 align:middle line:90%
you say, oh, I understand it.

01:10:42.060 --> 01:10:45.960 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it is more or
less getting used to it.

01:10:45.960 --> 01:10:49.350 align:middle line:84%
And indeed, at first sight,
it's not very intuitive

01:10:49.350 --> 01:10:51.660 align:middle line:84%
because it's not
something you can--

01:10:51.660 --> 01:10:55.500 align:middle line:84%
yeah, from your normal
experiences, et cetera.

01:10:55.500 --> 01:11:00.180 align:middle line:90%
But yeah, this is the--

01:11:00.180 --> 01:11:03.778 align:middle line:84%
but this is-- at the
fundamental level,

01:11:03.778 --> 01:11:05.820 align:middle line:84%
it's not that different
from energy conservation.

01:11:05.820 --> 01:11:09.010 align:middle line:84%
It's just some
symmetry, and then leads

01:11:09.010 --> 01:11:11.350 align:middle line:90%
to some conserved quantities.

01:11:11.350 --> 01:11:14.170 align:middle line:90%


01:11:14.170 --> 01:11:14.950 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:11:14.950 --> 01:11:16.867 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: If we have
another conserved charge,

01:11:16.867 --> 01:11:20.386 align:middle line:84%
like Q and now
electric charge and--

01:11:20.386 --> 01:11:24.310 align:middle line:84%
which ones do we call, I guess,
particle/antiparticle pairs?

01:11:24.310 --> 01:11:25.480 align:middle line:90%
Does that make sense?

01:11:25.480 --> 01:11:26.730 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that's right.

01:11:26.730 --> 01:11:29.760 align:middle line:84%
They can, in principle,
have multiple charges,

01:11:29.760 --> 01:11:31.510 align:middle line:84%
but the particle and
antiparticle, they're

01:11:31.510 --> 01:11:33.720 align:middle line:90%
always opposite.

01:11:33.720 --> 01:11:36.600 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, in terms of charges
they're always opposite--

01:11:36.600 --> 01:11:38.340 align:middle line:90%
whatever charges you have.

01:11:38.340 --> 01:11:40.650 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: What if there's
two different charges

01:11:40.650 --> 01:11:43.240 align:middle line:84%
that each one can have,
like a set of four things?

01:11:43.240 --> 01:11:44.670 align:middle line:90%
Is it a different language?

01:11:44.670 --> 01:11:45.810 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, I think--

01:11:45.810 --> 01:11:49.510 align:middle line:90%


01:11:49.510 --> 01:11:51.273 align:middle line:90%
yeah, you can have them--

01:11:51.273 --> 01:11:52.690 align:middle line:84%
but for particle
and antiparticle,

01:11:52.690 --> 01:11:54.648 align:middle line:90%
they're always opposite.

01:11:54.648 --> 01:11:56.190 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, they can have
multiple charges,

01:11:56.190 --> 01:11:57.615 align:middle line:90%
but they're always opposite.

01:11:57.615 --> 01:12:00.230 align:middle line:90%


01:12:00.230 --> 01:12:01.130 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

01:12:01.130 --> 01:12:04.610 align:middle line:90%


01:12:04.610 --> 01:12:06.240 align:middle line:90%
Good.

01:12:06.240 --> 01:12:12.520 align:middle line:84%
So this concludes our
discussion of the complex field.

01:12:12.520 --> 01:12:15.460 align:middle line:90%


01:12:15.460 --> 01:12:17.910 align:middle line:90%
So we have a few minutes--

01:12:17.910 --> 01:12:21.480 align:middle line:90%
then let's do to the next topic.

01:12:21.480 --> 01:12:24.460 align:middle line:90%


01:12:24.460 --> 01:12:59.110 align:middle line:84%
So hopefully-- so now,
let's talk about the concept

01:12:59.110 --> 01:13:01.860 align:middle line:90%
called the propagators.

01:13:01.860 --> 01:13:05.370 align:middle line:84%
So again, let's recall in
non-relativistic quantum

01:13:05.370 --> 01:13:08.170 align:middle line:90%
mechanics--

01:13:08.170 --> 01:13:12.190 align:middle line:84%
So this position vector
plays a key role.

01:13:12.190 --> 01:13:19.280 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
eigenvector of this x,

01:13:19.280 --> 01:13:21.670 align:middle line:90%
which is the position operator.

01:13:21.670 --> 01:13:23.350 align:middle line:90%
So again, I will--

01:13:23.350 --> 01:13:26.110 align:middle line:84%
yeah, let me just put
a hat here to emphasize

01:13:26.110 --> 01:13:28.450 align:middle line:90%
this is the operator.

01:13:28.450 --> 01:13:31.180 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
eigenvector of x.

01:13:31.180 --> 01:13:34.337 align:middle line:84%
And because this
plays a key role--

01:13:34.337 --> 01:13:36.670 align:middle line:84%
because we need to use this
to define the wave function.

01:13:36.670 --> 01:13:40.900 align:middle line:90%


01:13:40.900 --> 01:13:44.840 align:middle line:84%
And then the amplitude
of the wave function--

01:13:44.840 --> 01:13:47.260 align:middle line:84%
the square gives
us the probability

01:13:47.260 --> 01:13:49.740 align:middle line:90%
of a particle at location x.

01:13:49.740 --> 01:13:54.620 align:middle line:90%
So this is a crucial quantity.

01:13:54.620 --> 01:13:59.860 align:middle line:84%
So this language--
normally, we talk

01:13:59.860 --> 01:14:02.050 align:middle line:90%
about the Schrodinger picture.

01:14:02.050 --> 01:14:08.050 align:middle line:84%
You start with psi
x at t equal to 0,

01:14:08.050 --> 01:14:10.340 align:middle line:90%
and then you try to find--

01:14:10.340 --> 01:14:10.840 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

01:14:10.840 --> 01:14:14.455 align:middle line:84%
Or let me say, you
start at psi x--

01:14:14.455 --> 01:14:17.140 align:middle line:90%


01:14:17.140 --> 01:14:21.860 align:middle line:84%
say, t prime-- at
some t prime, you

01:14:21.860 --> 01:14:26.060 align:middle line:90%
want to find psi x at some t.

01:14:26.060 --> 01:14:29.420 align:middle line:84%
So this is the question
of quantum mechanics.

01:14:29.420 --> 01:14:31.910 align:middle line:84%
So if you know the wave
function at the initial time

01:14:31.910 --> 01:14:35.060 align:middle line:84%
and you want to find the wave
function at some future time.

01:14:35.060 --> 01:14:38.520 align:middle line:90%


01:14:38.520 --> 01:14:43.160 align:middle line:84%
So now let's imagine we
consider this question--

01:14:43.160 --> 01:14:44.000 align:middle line:90%
Heisenberg picture.

01:14:44.000 --> 01:14:49.590 align:middle line:90%


01:14:49.590 --> 01:14:57.420 align:middle line:84%
So in the Schrdinger picture,
there's just one eigenvector--

01:14:57.420 --> 01:14:59.430 align:middle line:84%
yeah, just one set
of eigenvectors

01:14:59.430 --> 01:15:03.170 align:middle line:90%
for x for different eigenvalues.

01:15:03.170 --> 01:15:09.440 align:middle line:84%
But for the Heisenberg picture
now, your position operator

01:15:09.440 --> 01:15:12.200 align:middle line:90%
now depends on time.

01:15:12.200 --> 01:15:14.690 align:middle line:84%
So the position operator
at different times,

01:15:14.690 --> 01:15:16.610 align:middle line:90%
they are different.

01:15:16.610 --> 01:15:20.110 align:middle line:84%
So now, if you want to talk
about the position eigenvector,

01:15:20.110 --> 01:15:22.480 align:middle line:90%
now you need the label.

01:15:22.480 --> 01:15:26.860 align:middle line:84%
So now, the position
eigenvector--

01:15:26.860 --> 01:15:29.020 align:middle line:90%
it's a t label.

01:15:29.020 --> 01:15:32.380 align:middle line:84%
This t does not mean that
this vector evolves with time.

01:15:32.380 --> 01:15:34.180 align:middle line:90%
It's just this is the label.

01:15:34.180 --> 01:15:36.220 align:middle line:84%
This means that this
is the eigenvector

01:15:36.220 --> 01:15:41.600 align:middle line:90%
of position vector at time t.

01:15:41.600 --> 01:15:46.580 align:middle line:90%


01:15:46.580 --> 01:15:49.430 align:middle line:84%
This just tells you this is
the eigenvector at time t.

01:15:49.430 --> 01:15:59.100 align:middle line:90%


01:15:59.100 --> 01:16:01.980 align:middle line:84%
And now, the question of--
this question of-- this is

01:16:01.980 --> 01:16:05.140 align:middle line:84%
the question of
quantum mechanics--

01:16:05.140 --> 01:16:09.550 align:middle line:84%
then can be reformulated
into a different equation.

01:16:09.550 --> 01:16:18.570 align:middle line:84%
So in this story, the
question of quantum mechanics

01:16:18.570 --> 01:16:20.100 align:middle line:90%
becomes the following--

01:16:20.100 --> 01:16:24.630 align:middle line:84%
what is the value
of this object?

01:16:24.630 --> 01:16:29.990 align:middle line:90%


01:16:29.990 --> 01:16:34.910 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you are in
the eigenstate--

01:16:34.910 --> 01:16:38.960 align:middle line:90%
you are the eigenvector--

01:16:38.960 --> 01:16:40.850 align:middle line:84%
you are in the
position eigenvector--

01:16:40.850 --> 01:16:45.170 align:middle line:84%
you are in the position
eigenstate at time t

01:16:45.170 --> 01:16:47.810 align:middle line:90%
prime with the value x prime.

01:16:47.810 --> 01:16:54.250 align:middle line:84%
And what's the amplitude for you
to go to location x at time t?

01:16:54.250 --> 01:16:57.910 align:middle line:84%
And I remember, this does
not involve time evolution.

01:16:57.910 --> 01:16:59.620 align:middle line:84%
This is just--
because one is labeled

01:16:59.620 --> 01:17:03.950 align:middle line:84%
in different eigenvector
at different time.

01:17:03.950 --> 01:17:06.440 align:middle line:84%
So if you know this
object, this is called--

01:17:06.440 --> 01:17:17.680 align:middle line:84%
this will be normally
denoted G. G--

01:17:17.680 --> 01:17:19.000 align:middle line:90%
this is called the propagator.

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:24.310 align:middle line:90%


01:17:24.310 --> 01:17:25.810 align:middle line:90%
This is called the propagator.

01:17:25.810 --> 01:17:31.930 align:middle line:84%
So if you know the propagator
of a quantum system,

01:17:31.930 --> 01:17:33.920 align:middle line:84%
then you have full
knowledge of that system,

01:17:33.920 --> 01:17:36.310 align:middle line:84%
so you already
solved that system.

01:17:36.310 --> 01:17:37.560 align:middle line:90%
Why?

01:17:37.560 --> 01:17:43.440 align:middle line:84%
Because say let's imagine
we want to find psi t x wave

01:17:43.440 --> 01:17:49.410 align:middle line:84%
function at time t,
and then by definition,

01:17:49.410 --> 01:17:50.980 align:middle line:90%
this is given by this.

01:17:50.980 --> 01:17:55.190 align:middle line:84%
So this is the Heisenberg
picture definition.

01:17:55.190 --> 01:18:00.580 align:middle line:84%
It's the psi overlap with the
position vector at time t.

01:18:00.580 --> 01:18:03.595 align:middle line:84%
And now, this is-- now, we can
insert a complete set of state.

01:18:03.595 --> 01:18:19.933 align:middle line:90%


01:18:19.933 --> 01:18:21.350 align:middle line:84%
I just insert a
complete set here.

01:18:21.350 --> 01:18:24.590 align:middle line:90%
Just this is the identity.

01:18:24.590 --> 01:18:31.450 align:middle line:90%
And then this object is just G.

01:18:31.450 --> 01:18:39.980 align:middle line:84%
So you just get G x t x prime
t prime, then psi t prime x

01:18:39.980 --> 01:18:40.480 align:middle line:90%
prime.

01:18:40.480 --> 01:18:43.920 align:middle line:90%


01:18:43.920 --> 01:18:46.150 align:middle line:90%
So if you know--

01:18:46.150 --> 01:18:50.410 align:middle line:84%
so yeah, so this just gave you
the wave function at t prime.

01:18:50.410 --> 01:18:53.010 align:middle line:90%
So now, if you load this--

01:18:53.010 --> 01:18:57.720 align:middle line:84%
given the initial wave function,
if you know the propagator,

01:18:57.720 --> 01:18:59.670 align:middle line:90%
you just need to do an integral.

01:18:59.670 --> 01:19:01.840 align:middle line:84%
Then, you find the
wave function here.

01:19:01.840 --> 01:19:04.980 align:middle line:84%
So the full knowledge of your
quantum mechanical system

01:19:04.980 --> 01:19:08.130 align:middle line:84%
essentially is encoded
in this propagator.

01:19:08.130 --> 01:19:11.190 align:middle line:90%


01:19:11.190 --> 01:19:13.320 align:middle line:90%
It's encoded in this propagator.

01:19:13.320 --> 01:19:18.210 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, now, we want
to talk about what

01:19:18.210 --> 01:19:21.960 align:middle line:84%
is the analog of this object,
say, in relativistic quantum

01:19:21.960 --> 01:19:24.060 align:middle line:90%
field theory?

01:19:24.060 --> 01:19:27.180 align:middle line:84%
In quantum field theory, how
do we define a propagator,

01:19:27.180 --> 01:19:32.280 align:middle line:84%
and what is the analog of
the position eigenstate,

01:19:32.280 --> 01:19:33.990 align:middle line:90%
say, in quantum field theory?

01:19:33.990 --> 01:19:36.950 align:middle line:90%
And we will discuss next time.

01:19:36.950 --> 01:19:42.000 align:middle line:90%